# Arrays in Java

Imagine a classroom with 30 students. Without arrays, you would need 30 separate variables: `score1`, `score2`, ..., `score30`. An **array** stores multiple values of the same type under one name, accessed by a numeric index.

## Declaring and Creating Arrays

```java
// Method 1: declare then allocate
int[] scores = new int[5];       // 5 slots, all initialised to 0

// Method 2: declare and initialise with values
int[] marks = {85, 92, 78, 95, 88};

// Method 3: typed array with new keyword
String[] names = new String[]{"Rahul", "Priya", "Amit"};
```

## Accessing Elements

Java arrays use **zero-based indexing** — the first element is at index 0:

```java
int[] arr = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
System.out.println(arr[0]);   // 10 — first element
System.out.println(arr[4]);   // 50 — last element
System.out.println(arr.length); // 5 — count of elements (not a method)
```

Accessing `arr[5]` would throw an `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException`.

## Modifying Elements

```java
marks[2] = 90;   // replace index 2 (was 78, now 90)
```

## Iterating Over Arrays

```java
// Classic for — use when you need the index
for (int i = 0; i < scores.length; i++) {
    System.out.println("Index " + i + ": " + scores[i]);
}

// Enhanced for — use when you only need the value
for (int score : scores) {
    System.out.println(score);
}
```

## Common Array Operations

```java
// Sum all elements
int total = 0;
for (int v : arr) total += v;

// Find maximum
int max = arr[0];
for (int v : arr) if (v > max) max = v;

// Sort (ascending) — from java.util.Arrays
java.util.Arrays.sort(arr);   // modifies arr in place
```

## 2D Arrays

A 2D array stores rows and columns — like a spreadsheet:

```java
int[][] matrix = {
    {1, 2, 3},
    {4, 5, 6},
    {7, 8, 9}
};
System.out.println(matrix[1][2]);  // row 1, column 2 → 6
```

In the code example below, you will see array creation, iteration, and the accumulator pattern applied to a class score report.

codeExample.code:
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String[] names  = {"Rahul", "Priya", "Amit", "Sneha", "Vikram"};
        int[]    scores = {88, 95, 72, 91, 67};

        // Compute total, average, highest
        int    total   = 0;
        int    highest = scores[0];
        String topName = names[0];

        for (int i = 0; i < scores.length; i++) {
            total += scores[i];
            if (scores[i] > highest) {
                highest = scores[i];
                topName = names[i];     // track who has the highest
            }
        }

        double average = (double) total / scores.length;

        // Print report
        System.out.println("=== Class Report ===");
        for (int i = 0; i < names.length; i++) {
            String grade = scores[i] >= 90 ? "A" :
                           scores[i] >= 75 ? "B" : "C";
            System.out.printf("%-10s %3d  %s%n",
                              names[i], scores[i], grade);
        }
        System.out.println("---");
        System.out.printf("Average : %.1f%n", average);
        System.out.printf("Top     : %s (%d)%n", topName, highest);
    }
}

